        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=pop-science">pop-science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=nature">nature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=travel-lit">travel-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=20th-c-classics">20th-c-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=six-stars">six-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=write-a-review-you-lazy-git">write-a-review-you-lazy-git</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=nyrb">nyrb</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3156241642" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15433116577174975733">4.5*<br/>Ah, I recognise cycle navigating that chilly mud from my fenland childhood.<br/>This seemed like it was written in a slower time, free from today’s anxious rush to no more important endeavour. Plentiful intricate detail given for reflection and creative seasonal simile/metaphor. The Peregrine’s movement and appearance leaves Baker awestruck ....but it is rarely reduced to anthropomorphic sweetness (Baker acknowledges this), more glassy eyed singular absence, ‘the overwhelming indifference of natu</span>
  <span id="freeText15433116577174975733" style="display:none">4.5*<br />Ah, I recognise cycle navigating that chilly mud from my fenland childhood.<br />This seemed like it was written in a slower time, free from today’s anxious rush to no more important endeavour. Plentiful intricate detail given for reflection and creative seasonal simile/metaphor. The Peregrine’s movement and appearance leaves Baker awestruck ....but it is rarely reduced to anthropomorphic sweetness (Baker acknowledges this), more glassy eyed singular absence, ‘the overwhelming indifference of nature’ (-stolen from Werner Herzog- ‘Grizzly Man’ 2005). Although a link is sought the owl offers ‘more’ human connection in a matter of moments with it’s comparatively benign clownishness. Other animals were somewhat a relief from the peregrine’s necessary lifetime hunt. At one point it even appears to size Baker up for elevenses ....RTC.<br /><br />Recognition of this book from someone who isn’t losing the fight with language:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/15/the-peregrine-by-ja-baker-nature-writing">https://www.theguardian.com/books/201...</a><br /><br />Progress notes/quotes too, in case you are so inclined.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15433116577174975733" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


